text: Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us. This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy. And here are your hosts. This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. How many science fiction works feature spacecraft capable of planet hopping, interstellar travel, or even galaxy galloping? Yet in our experience, we know it takes several days' travel to reach even the moon, and years to reach the nearest planets. Travel to the stars is presently unthinkable. In space opera, the writer usually invokes some kind of faster-than-light drive, which glosses over the basics of the special theory of relativity. We asked physicist and science fiction writer Robert Forward how it may be possible to travel faster than light. When you talk about going faster than light, really what you want to do is get from here to there, without traveling all the steps in between. If you can do that, then you can go faster than light. There's two ways, at least, that I know to do that. One is to find a space warp. You jump into the space warp, you go into a hyperspace, and then you come out of another space warp somewhere else in our universe. And if you can do that in a time shorter than it takes you to travel over the top line, then you've done that. An amazing thing about it is the Einstein general theory of relativity has space warps in it. Going through a space warp is one way to get around the speed of light limit. And what's the second way? Then the other way to go faster than the speed of light is to destroy the space between you and where you want to go. Now this space drive theory was invented by a student of Roger Penrose. He's a scientific expert and relativist that works with Hawking on gravitation. He's working on a thing called twister theory. And in the twister theory, the real universe is not what we see. That's only a reduced image of it. The real universe is an eight-dimensional universe that's made up of twisters. And the twisters not only make up all the particles in the space and time that we live in, it even makes up the space and the time. It takes a certain collection of twisters to make up a point in space. It takes another collection of twisters to make up a point in time. This collection of twisters is a fairly uniform thing, and that's why we see space as it is, according to Penrose. Now we don't know whether the twister theory is correct, but Roger is hoping that it will turn out to be an accurate method, I mean, accurate theory for the universe. So how does one build a faster-than-light drive based on the twister theory of Penrose and his students? If you warp the twister space too much, give it a real strong warp, then it's no longer ordered well enough to make a piece of space or a piece of time. So if you take a piece of twister space and you warp it badly, the space and the time that it used to make now disappears. It's no longer there. So their version of a different kind of a faster-than-light drive is you take a spacecraft up, you get it out in the way from the planets and so forth, and then you turn on the twister warping machine in your spacecraft on the side towards Alpha Centauri, and you just warp that space so much that you warp that twister space so much that the space-time between here and Alpha Centauri disappears. And what you'll see if you're sitting in a spacecraft is that all of a sudden Alpha Centauri just come right towards you, and then pretty soon you look out one window, you see the sun, you look out the other window, you'll see Alpha Centauri. Then the machine inside the spacecraft unwarps the space, but on the other side of the spacecraft, and all that space now reappears between the spacecraft and the sun. You watch the sun recede off into the distance while you stay there with Alpha Centauri. So that's another way to get there. You just get rid of the space between here and there. The Science Fiction Radio Show, Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us. This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy. And here are your hosts. This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. No other field has fans as distinctive and intense, some would even say as fanatical, as science fiction does. Every year there are hundreds of conventions around the country, from small local affairs to the Incredible World Convention, at which fans gather. They come for various reasons, of course. To socialize with like-minded people, to meet science fiction and fantasy authors, to buy books at the dealer's tables. There's one particular type of fan with a special, consuming interest, costuming and masquerade. Most conventions, therefore, have a masquerade section, a contest for fans who have made and presented a costume from some science fiction or fantasy work. The Science Fiction Radio Show spoke with Teresa Patterson, a fan who has won numerous awards for her science fiction and fantasy costuming. She says a few years ago she was hooked on Star Trek, but do nothing about fandom. But one day after Star Trek, there was a big advertisement for a Star Trek convention in Dallas. And it was going to have some of the stars there and everything, and I'd never heard of such a thing. But it sounded like a lot of fun, so we went down, and then I ran into nearly 1,500 to 2,000 fans who also liked Star Trek, who also had a reason for coming to science fiction and fantasy, and had been touched by Star Trek because of this feeling they had. And all of a sudden I had a family and a place to belong. And I've been an avid fan ever since, going to as many conventions as I could. And one aspect of this convention was costuming. And I'd always been sort of interested in theater and that sort of thing, but never really involved. But here were all these people who weren't really into theater and weren't performers, but they had all these wonderful costumes and were going up and doing the masquerades. The next time they had a convention, I was ready, and I had my first costume. It was a very poorly made Mirror Mirror costume from the Star Trek episode Mirror Mirror. But it was a beginning, and it was something, and all of a sudden I was involved, and I had a part in a world where in my main life I didn't have much of anything that I really belonged to. And through fandom and science fiction and belonging to that world, I eventually learned how to belong in a normal world again. And basically, it changed my entire life. I actually even became popular in high school, which at the time that I started in fandom, I would have thought that popularity was something I would never see. So, and then it grew from there. I became a theater and drama major at UTA, and I now work as a professional singer and performer and do a lot of costuming with that job and freelance costuming. But my first love is still making characters come alive on the stage at science fiction and fantasy conventions. Because I think that what I was searching for at the time was a reality that I could fit into, and I think that's what the other fans are searching for. And the masquerade gives me a chance to make that dream become a reality. We asked her to give us an example of bringing a science fiction character to life through costuming. One of our most successful costume skits that we designed, and I had some other people with me at the time, we went to Worldcon in Boston, and we had a young fellow who was a good friend of mine and my little sister did a Star Wars skit together. But what they did was the lights darkened and the Star Wars theme came up, and all of a sudden, Luke Skywalker came flying through the air doing somersaults onto the stage, stopped and did a one-handed handstand, very precariously balancing, using the Force to hold him up. And then Yoda came slowly onto stage, nodding wisely, and instructing him on the use of the Force. He didn't get it right the first time, then he tried again the second time, and finally succeeded with a perfect one-handed handstand, balancing with the use of the Force. And then leapt up, did a couple more flying leaps and somersaults in the middle of the air across the stage and left. standing ovation by 9,000 screaming people who, for them, Star Wars was alive. We'll talk with Teresa Patterson about fans and costuming next time. Patterson believes that the best costumes are those that make the science fiction or fantasy character come to life for the viewers. Therefore, in addition to constructing the costume itself, she also creates a setting and sort of a brief script to put the character in. She takes us through one of her creations. Now, I also have another one that has been extremely successful. It's called Morgan Le Fay. And the character, basically, I was sitting around trying to think of what is a really way-out character that's not all that well-known, but that could command the stage and make that same kind of reality come about. And it occurred to me that very little has been done with the sorceress, Morgan Le Fay, who's from the Arthurian legend and who was the one that eventually defeated Merlin. And I thought, if I can make this character do a spell on stage so that the audience really believes it, that that would be an excellent kind of costume to do. So I designed the costume. And of course, it's different than designing a costume for a movie character or a television character because it was completely up to my imagination what I wanted to do with it. So I used a lot of reds and blacks and lots of gold and to create a total effect of color but somber evil color and made a very large headdress with lots of sparkles on it to catch the light and designed it in such a way so that it would give the impression of an evil sorceress who had a lot of power and was a ruler in her own right and designed the cloak so that it would actually fold out into a half circle so that it would look like bat wings on the back. The costume was beautiful, but that's not enough. What Patterson had to come up with was something for Morgan Le Fay to do. Then she had to locate a soundtrack that would somehow convey the evil and menace of the sorceress. Patterson did both of these things. Then she added a little extra to the sound effects. And then I added a soundtrack record which had thunder and lightning on it and went into my handy-dandy little stereo set in the middle of the living room, bought a bunch of patch cords from Radio Shack so that the room looked like Spaghetti'sville and patched it all together and using a normal hand mic and a reverb effect from the speakers being on at the same time as the recording managed to get an evil reverberating sound to the voice, lightning and thunder in the background, this awesome evil music building and flowing and a high climax and then fading out in the distance. So I had a wonderful soundtrack and if the mic failed, I'd still be fine because I had it all on tape. Finally, she describes the presentation of the character at a convention before a large audience. And the way the actual skit came off was something like this. The stage would darken and then you'd see a red glow moving up onto the stage and you'd see just the outline of this bizarre golden mask and a red-garbed woman holding the red globe. And the music starts and starts to build and all of a sudden the spell starts and then suddenly there's a burst of flame from the red globe. And as the spell builds and she starts summoning the darkness, the room gets darker for a moment and then there's another burst of flame and the room starts to lighten just a little bit and the spell builds and builds until finally she banishes the light from her and says darkness be gone and then blasts this huge shot of fire blue flame straight up into the sky and the darkness is gone. And then she tells you that she is Morgan Le Fay and then demonstrates the costume and shows the wide wings of the bat and slowly walks off as the thunder fades into the distance. Again, I got a standing ovation. The costume has never not won a prize. It has always been first and second everywhere I've taken it. And there are better costumes but it comes to life and that's what the people are looking for is a way to bring their fantasies and their dreams into reality so they can touch them so it's something they can really have a tangible experience from. More with Teresa Patterson next time. This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Teresa Patterson is a science fiction fantasy fan who was turned on by the idea of making familiar characters from the field come to life for others. She goes to science fiction conventions with carefully constructed costumes and colorful skits. She enters the masquerade or some costuming competition with her creations and has won many awards. Costuming is a fascinating part of science fiction fandom. We observed that there must be some acting ability that goes along with it. Of course. But actually, I think there's a bit of actress or actor in almost everyone who's into the fandom scene at all and even people who aren't. It's just a matter of whether we can actually do something with it or not. A lot of people just assume, well, that'll never happen. I'll never get to do anything with it and they forget about that part of their personality. I'm a little more stubborn. I intend to do it professionally eventually and to some extent am doing that now with my performing as a singer and dancer with the singing telegram companies and as a model and so forth. And I've been in two science fiction movies as an extra, Logan's Run and Lathe of Heaven, which both were a lot of fun. But it doesn't take an actor or an actress to do these kind of things and I've seen a lot of really wonderful skits and costumes and performances pulled off by people who had never even considered the idea of being professional actors or actresses. They just want to make it real. And that's all acting ever was, was just trying to make something real and recreate something. It's just that what we do is a little different than your typical stage play. But it should be no less entertaining and we're trying to create it so that it's no less entertaining. Patterson usually works with a group of friends in performing her masquerade skits who wondered how newcomers took to costuming. Do they become converts fairly quickly? We don't have anyone who's ever met or joined our group that hasn't immediately ended up in a costume. Sometimes under protest the first time but they always end up under a costume and then they always want more and more costumes and the next thing you know we've got a whole new set of costumers. When we went to Boston we took five people in four different costume skits. These five people I was the only one who'd ever been to a WorldCom before. Most of them had never even been to a major convention before. All they knew was they wanted to do the masquerade. They loved science fiction and fantasy and fandom and they wanted to do the masquerade and they had a lot of creativity and they were willing to listen to suggestions and we all worked together and we came away with four awards. People who nobody had ever heard of before we went up there to the WorldCon and won four of the top awards. Best Presentation Overall, First Runner-Up for Best Presentation, Star Wars Special Award Prize and First Runner-Up for Best Fantasy. We asked Patterson how she taught herself to do the elaborate costuming she's doing now. I still don't know what I'm doing now. I've learned a lot from other people and from lots of trial and error, mostly trial and error. I discovered fabric glue when I was in desperation and it works wonderfully on all kinds of things. When I started costuming, I really didn't know anything about sewing at all. The idea of making clothes was the farthest thing from my mind and it just happened that I needed a costume and I had to figure out how to create this thing that you couldn't possibly buy in a store by its very nature and the first costumes were very much trial and error but since then, I've learned a lot of shortcuts, shortcuts that an average seamstress would probably never use because they learned all the rules and I didn't and I try to pass on those shortcuts and at a lot of the major conventions, they have workshops where they discuss costuming and shortcuts that other people have found and stage techniques and there are books and magazines out that cover costuming and makeup and easy ways to do all these things. Any fan who's seen some of Teresa Patterson's work can't help but be impressed. She's made many characters from fantasy and science fiction live. We'll talk about some other aspects of fandom on our next show. This will be our final show with Teresa Patterson, science fiction fan and costume designer. Patterson talks about the various types of science fiction fans. And our listeners should keep in mind that in fan terminology, fin is the plural of fan. There are actually several different level of fans. There are new fin, which are people who just discovered that, oh, you mean there's somebody else that reads this stuff besides me? There are true fin, who are the people who go to conventions on a live and die situation and fandom is a way of life and will sell whatever they can sell at the dealers' tables if they can make enough money to get back and forth between the conventions and who literally, the convention society, is their social life. Then there are a whole scope of people in between. There are what we call closet fans who are the people who read the books, who watch the shows, who go to the movies, but who have absolutely no idea that there's any kind of organization out there whatsoever. There are the slightly organized fans, which are people who realize that there is organization who maybe go to a con every now and then, who every now and then get a chance to meet their favorite author, but who really aren't that much into the convention scene. It's just something that they like and every now and then they like to express the fact that they enjoy it. And then, of course, there are the professional fin, which are people who through their professions one way or the other have somehow gotten tied up with the science fiction or fantasy genre and because they deal with it every day or part of every day and because they must like it or they wouldn't deal with it to some extent. They're fan too. Serious science fiction fans who attend conventions live in a weird sort of world with its own activities and even its own vocabulary. Both these aspects of fandom are illustrated in the word folk singing. We asked Patterson to explain it to us. Well, basically, like any other, when you take fandom as a microcosm of people and that this is their social life when they're at a convention, you have to deal with the fact that social life includes entertainment. And if you're into science fiction and fantasy and you're doing something special like a convention, you don't want to go out and entertain yourself by going to the local bar or the local disco. That's boring. You want to do something that's uniquely fandom. And so something that was developed through fandom is a thing called filk singing. Filk singing is folk singing, sort of. Basically, filk singing is a creation of songs that are performed by one person or many person on or off key, it makes no difference, that were written specifically for the audience of science fiction and fantasy listeners. Patterson says there can be different kinds of filk singing, but that they all fulfill a need among science fiction fans. Now, some of filk singing is very simple. It simply involves taking a tune from a normal song and changing the words around to have something to do with science fiction or fantasy, and usually those are funny and they're the kind that you can get a lot of giggles off and everyone joins in. But the more serious element is original songs that deal with very serious ideas like the fact that man's finally reaching for space and the Columbia's here or the fact that when are we really going to get to be dancing on the moon by the time it actually happens I'll be too old and things like that. And filking is a whole type of folk singing strictly for fans. And some fans don't like it because they don't like the taking of other people's music and putting other lyrics to it. But for most fans, it's a wonderful outlet for getting to know other people and just sit around at night when there's nothing else to do and sing songs and get a very close type of camaraderie that you only get in some other kind of very close-knit group. Not all conventions have filk singing but the more intimate ones where it really is a social life type situation do because it's a very big part of the social life. Patterson's enthusiasm for science fiction and science fiction fandom is obvious and infectious.
